# Kal — Backend Rules

## Backend role
The backend supports the core product loop:
- authentication
- user profile storage
- target calculation persistence
- meal records
- daily aggregates
- photo storage
- AI analysis orchestration
- validation of structured AI output

Do not add backend capabilities outside the MVP unless explicitly requested.

## Preferred stack
Use a simple backend aligned with:
- Supabase / Postgres
- object storage for meal images
- server-side functions for sensitive orchestration
- typed data contracts where possible

## Data modeling principles
Favor a straightforward relational model.

Typical entities should remain close to:
- users
- user_profiles
- goals / targets
- meals
- meal_items or meal_analysis results
- daily summaries if needed
- uploaded meal photos

Avoid premature complexity:
- no event sourcing
- no microservices
- no unnecessary queueing systems
- no speculative analytics schemas

## Schema design
- Use clear table names
- Use explicit foreign keys
- Prefer timestamp columns for created/updated tracking
- Keep nullable fields intentional
- Add constraints where they protect data quality
- Write migrations clearly and incrementally

## Source of truth
- Persist core user and meal data in the backend
- Do not rely on client-only state for critical records
- Server-side validation should protect structured AI outputs before persistence

## Security
- Apply least privilege principles
- Use row-level security where appropriate
- Never expose secrets in client code
- Keep sensitive AI orchestration and validation on the server when possible

## API and function design
- Keep functions narrow and task-specific
- Prefer explicit inputs and outputs
- Return predictable structured payloads
- Validate all incoming data
- Fail clearly when data is incomplete or malformed

## Reliability
- Handle AI failures gracefully
- Handle image upload failures gracefully
- Avoid partial writes when possible
- Preserve data consistency between photo upload, analysis result, and saved meal

## Observability
At minimum:
- log important failures
- log invalid AI payloads
- make debugging possible without excessive noise

Do not build a large observability platform unless explicitly requested.

## Performance
Optimize for simplicity first.
Only optimize after clear need.
That said:
- avoid obviously inefficient queries
- index foreign keys and key lookup paths
- avoid returning unnecessary payload size

## Migrations and changes
When changing schema:
- write additive migrations first when possible
- avoid destructive changes unless explicitly requested
- explain data impact
- keep migrations readable and reversible where practical

## Backend discipline
Do not:
- build infrastructure for hypothetical scale
- introduce services not needed for the MVP
- add unrelated endpoints
- mix experimental product ideas into the backend

Always:
- support the current Kal MVP
- keep contracts stable
- validate structured data carefully
- prefer simple, maintainable systems